brendan fay andrew w mellon fellowship of scholars in the humanities skip to navigation home support the center about people apply events contact brendan fay department of art history stanford university brendan fay is an art historian working in photography and twentieth century art he earned a ba in art history and mathematics from the university of michigan has held internships at the museum of modern art the national gallery of art and the harvard art museum and received his phd in history of art and architecture from harvard university in 2009 his current book project examines strategies of abstraction in american photography between 1940 and 1960 drawing together the pictorial and pedagogical practices of minor white aaron siskind and harry callahan the book explores midcentury photography's engagement with the all over as a formal and experiential problem while grounding that engagement in the institutional imperatives of the postwar university his research interests include problems of composition and noncomposition in artistic pedagogy questions of disciplinary formation and historical models of reading and experiencing photographs and the physical relationship between cameras and bodies his 2009 10 course offerings in the stanford department of art and art history included photography and its histories a survey of the medium's form and uses and a seminar on photography and abstraction in 2010 11 he will offer a seminar on performance and photography co taught with prof kate elswit and an undergraduate course in the material and social life of photographs since 1950 people fellows faculty and staff alumni terms of use copyright complaints 2010 stanford university stanford humanities center 424 santa teresa st stanford ca 94305 tel 650 723 3052
